00:12:06,131 --> 00:12:08,892
reacting to the feedback, letting them know what we're incorporating.

233
00:12:09,352 --> 00:12:12,313
And then at the end of the week, we would re-release that design document.

234
00:12:12,993 --> 00:12:16,554
That design document would feel very different from the one we first put out.

235
00:12:18,335 --> 00:12:20,476
Now, obviously you know good design doc processes,

236
00:12:20,516 --> 00:12:23,037
but many of you are designers or developers.

237
00:12:24,037 --> 00:12:25,598
But when it comes to pushing one out to the players,

238
00:12:25,618 --> 00:12:26,778
there are a lot of things to keep in mind.

239
00:12:27,419 --> 00:12:28,779
Please do choose your update wisely.

240
00:12:28,799 --> 00:12:30,600
You're going to find out very soon

241
00:12:30,980 --> 00:12:34,401
the cost of producing a design document for the players is huge.

242
00:12:35,452 --> 00:12:36,032
It's massive.

243
00:12:36,492 --> 00:12:37,953
So doing it for niche updates,

244
00:12:38,513 --> 00:12:39,794
you get disproportional success.

245
00:12:40,154 --> 00:12:40,955
It will not be worth it.

246
00:12:41,215 --> 00:12:43,456
So choose those updates that are broad, that are universal.

247
00:12:44,177 --> 00:12:46,318
And you have to be so hugely confident in your update.

248
00:12:47,199 --> 00:12:49,080
If you're putting out a design document that's shabby,

249
00:12:50,300 --> 00:12:51,421
then your players will begin to feel

250
00:12:51,461 --> 00:12:52,282
that you just don't care,

251
00:12:52,302 --> 00:12:53,422
that you're just not putting in the effort.

252
00:12:54,423 --> 00:12:55,644
Be really confident in the update.

253
00:12:55,684 --> 00:12:58,926
Don't treat it, treat this design document as a beater.

254
00:12:59,466 --> 00:13:00,807
This should be the most finished design document

255
00:13:00,847 --> 00:13:01,727
you have ever put out.

256
00:13:02,168 --> 00:13:03,428
Everybody should have signed off on it.

257
00:13:05,026 --> 00:13:08,028
It would need to be kind of presented in the flow of user experience.

258
00:13:08,348 --> 00:13:11,770
Describe it in the way that the player interacts with your content.

259
00:13:12,711 --> 00:13:16,673
They will be moving through geographically, chronologically, through your content.

260
00:13:16,953 --> 00:13:19,515
Tell them the story of going through your content.

261
00:13:19,875 --> 00:13:21,656
This is the language of their game experience.

262
00:13:21,896 --> 00:13:24,338
So you're going to have to completely refactor your design document to that.

263
00:13:25,738 --> 00:13:26,259
Add reasoning.

264
00:13:27,051 --> 00:13:31,759
There's a lot of things in that design document that will feel strange without the context of your acceptance criteria.

265
00:13:32,099 --> 00:13:35,225
You've likely put those, already created your core aims or acceptance criteria anyway.

266
00:13:35,525 --> 00:13:39,452
Put them at the top, players will start to understand that your decision is not arbitrary.

267
00:13:39,973 --> 00:13:41,395
And also understand the level of detail.

268
00:13:42,607 --> 00:13:48,632
If you're putting in drop rates, XP rates, monetization details, 90% of your feedback

269
00:13:48,672 --> 00:13:50,734
will fixate on those details.

270
00:13:51,175 --> 00:13:54,798
It might be that one was overpowered or underpowered, or maybe there was an error.

271
00:13:55,499 --> 00:13:58,161
Understand that players will pick this apart and will not give you feedback on the rest

272
00:13:58,181 --> 00:13:58,362
of it.

273
00:13:58,442 --> 00:14:01,204
It might be that you want that, maybe you're so confident in the efficacy of the rest of

274
00:14:01,224 --> 00:14:01,665
your design.

275
00:14:02,565 --> 00:14:03,887
And really break it video and text.

276
00:14:04,187 --> 00:14:06,589
We didn't see any cannibalization between the different media.

277
00:14:06,749 --> 00:14:07,550
It means you get it out there.

278
00:14:10,015 --> 00:14:13,077
So the flaws, it's a huge intensity of work.

279
00:14:13,197 --> 00:14:14,818
Putting together, doing the design process,

280
00:14:14,939 --> 00:14:15,899
the published design process,

281
00:14:16,119 --> 00:14:18,261
was 120 hours of designer work.

282
00:14:19,842 --> 00:14:21,203
And understand that it delays development.

283
00:14:21,644 --> 00:14:24,366
Your design phase is going to swallow up

284
00:14:24,386 --> 00:14:25,707
probably another two weeks of work.

285
00:14:25,967 --> 00:14:26,547
Build that in.

286
00:14:27,148 --> 00:14:27,748
Maybe a cost.

287
00:14:28,349 --> 00:14:29,770
For many of you, you work agile.

288
00:14:29,930 --> 00:14:31,812
Maybe you don't even do a design document.

289
00:14:32,432 --> 00:14:33,593
Maybe it's kind of iterative

290
00:14:33,613 --> 00:14:34,714
and created over the course of the design.

291
00:14:34,754 --> 00:14:36,115
Maybe your design document is more visual.

292
00:14:37,143 --> 00:14:38,824
This may be a deal breaker for you.

293
00:14:39,045 --> 00:14:42,907
If you don't put out longer, more text-oriented design documents,

294
00:14:42,927 --> 00:14:44,528
it may be that the work to convert it is too much.

295
00:14:45,348 --> 00:14:47,770
And there is a potential negative impact on your current content.

296
00:14:47,830 --> 00:14:49,671
Understand, if this is an ongoing game,

297
00:14:50,231 --> 00:14:52,933
that if you're putting out something, a design for something that improves on

298
00:14:53,894 --> 00:14:56,375
something existing in the game, they may not play that content anymore.

299
00:14:56,395 --> 00:14:59,717
You may be manipulating your economy by putting this information out there.

300
00:15:00,017 --> 00:15:01,858
Understand the effect on your current game content.

301
00:15:03,326 --> 00:15:06,788
And do not expect wide ranging feedback from your player base.

302
00:15:07,848 --> 00:15:21,454
So players, as we've seen from the kind of the legions, the forum, the hundreds and thousands of forum posts and social media feedback that we received on our published design documents, is that players do not give creative feedback. They do not offer alternatives.

303
00:15:22,495 --> 00:15:24,075
They don't often not very constructive.

304
00:15:25,747 --> 00:15:27,187
But that's fine. We'll go into that in a minute.

305
00:15:27,387 --> 00:15:28,828
And they do not have a full deck of lenses.

306
00:15:29,148 --> 00:15:31,768
They won't understand tutorialization,

307
00:15:32,029 --> 00:15:33,729
kind of narrative grounding.

308
00:15:33,749 --> 00:15:35,250
They won't understand a lot of these things.

309
00:15:35,470 --> 00:15:36,710
So understand what the players will give you.

310
00:15:38,991 --> 00:15:41,191
But design.benefits, there's more participation than you'd think.

311
00:15:41,632 --> 00:15:44,112
For our Elf City design documents, which are the first ones we put out,

312
00:15:44,512 --> 00:15:47,333
one-third of our player base read those design documents.

313
00:15:48,033 --> 00:15:50,194
Fewer than one-third could actually play it on launch.

314
00:15:50,794 --> 00:15:51,875
Players were really interested in it.

315
00:15:51,895 --> 00:15:53,475
They really wanted to get involved with it.

316
00:15:54,304 --> 00:15:57,807
And while their feedback is limited to certain things, it is hugely valuable.

317
00:15:58,068 --> 00:16:02,131
It comes in the context of, I will play this, or I will not play this.

318
00:16:03,192 --> 00:16:07,236
While that is limited, that is ultimately what you're looking for from your content.

319
00:16:07,556 --> 00:16:10,299
You want to know if the people who are playing your game will play the game.

320
00:16:13,261 --> 00:16:17,165
And players have begun to understand, or get a better sense of the realistic kind of

321
00:16:17,485 --> 00:16:19,767
what happens when we're designing content or developing content.

322
00:16:20,678 --> 00:16:22,159
Content doesn't just appear in the game.

323
00:16:22,739 --> 00:16:25,681
They often felt like we just treated our community as a beta.

324
00:16:26,241 --> 00:16:27,822
That we would just throw content out there.

325
00:16:28,242 --> 00:16:30,724
And because they only saw nerfs or improvements,

326
00:16:31,324 --> 00:16:33,045
they believed that we just treated the whole of the game

327
00:16:33,305 --> 00:16:34,626
as a beta phase.

328
00:16:35,966 --> 00:16:38,108
Now understand how long it takes to create something.

329
00:16:38,408 --> 00:16:40,729
They have more belief and faith in us as designers.

330
00:16:41,450 --> 00:16:42,110
That's very valuable.

331
00:16:43,191 --> 00:16:44,932
And there's a huge change to release day.

332
00:16:44,972 --> 00:16:46,012
This is something we didn't expect.

333
00:16:46,032 --> 00:16:46,953
Release day is awesome.

334
00:16:48,296 --> 00:16:51,677
Players were often kind of on other content that didn't have design documents published.

335
00:16:51,817 --> 00:16:53,018
There was an expectation gap.

336
00:16:54,038 --> 00:16:55,518
They kind of, they got on the hype train

337
00:16:56,119 --> 00:16:57,739
and believed it to be something that it wasn't.

338
00:16:57,759 --> 00:16:59,480
They extrapolated far further.

339
00:16:59,500 --> 00:17:01,480
And then when it was launched, there was kind of,

340
00:17:01,741 --> 00:17:02,881
this isn't quite what I wanted.

341
00:17:03,481 --> 00:17:05,242
That thinned down, smaller gap.

342
00:17:05,802 --> 00:17:07,082
It reduced orientation. They don't need,

343
00:17:07,663 --> 00:17:09,763
fewer players need tutorialization or orientation.

344
00:17:09,783 --> 00:17:11,604
They're going straight to the content that they want to get to.

345
00:17:11,904 --> 00:17:13,184
Again, that's valuable to your player base.

346
00:17:14,070 --> 00:17:18,675
It's reduced the chance of post-launch issues, the number of times that we have put an update into our game

347
00:17:18,895 --> 00:17:23,900
that's been completely derailed by one thing that needs to be nerfed or powered up a little bit more.

348
00:17:25,364 --> 00:17:50,820
Some fix that has to be made and all the conversation again is fixated on that. It directs conversation where you want it. And in our case, and something that's very valuable, I would encourage you to try this is put is don't put everything in your design document. Try putting little Easter eggs into your content that players will search out on launch day and let them know that they're there so they can go find them. We found a kind of great great value in that, and that meant that not everything was kind of in that design document. There was still something to find.

349
00:17:52,508 --> 00:17:54,930
So takeaways, expensive and time consuming,

350
00:17:55,030 --> 00:17:56,450
only suits a limited range of projects,

351
00:17:56,630 --> 00:17:59,071
but as a tool, it does throw a spotlight on your content,

352
00:17:59,312 --> 00:18:00,712
really does improve that relationship,

353
00:18:01,272 --> 00:18:03,553
and does make your release day kind of stress-free.

