00:18:05,334 --> 00:18:06,335
Okay, so the next one.

355
00:18:06,435 --> 00:18:09,276
So what happens when you do a fully crowdsourced game design?

356
00:18:09,696 --> 00:18:11,557
We came up with something bespoke called RuneLabs.

357
00:18:11,577 --> 00:18:16,059
You can kind of see the process across the bottom there.

358
00:18:16,619 --> 00:18:18,340
And we were feeling the glow of the design documents.

359
00:18:18,360 --> 00:18:19,761
The players loved the design documents.

360
00:18:20,757 --> 00:18:25,340
And we thought the natural extension was to bring them into making designs for our game.

361
00:18:25,901 --> 00:18:29,083
It also meant that we could kind of push through and talk to press.

362
00:18:29,423 --> 00:18:34,206
Press might be interested in a game that was designed by our players.

363
00:18:34,707 --> 00:18:38,069
So we start by players generating an idea and adding that to our database.

364
00:18:38,269 --> 00:18:39,570
We now have effectively a database.

365
00:18:40,691 --> 00:18:43,052
Players then upvote those designs that they really like.

366
00:18:43,653 --> 00:18:48,816
And then we take the top five, top four, top three, whatever we agreed for that month.

367
00:18:50,376 --> 00:18:55,598
And those are then put in game as a poll people in game and choose the update. They want to go in.

368
00:18:56,938 --> 00:19:02,620
Is a little example of some of the ideas we got. I really don't know what 101 things to do with this thick of bamboo is. I probably don't want to know.

369
00:19:03,960 --> 00:19:05,100
But what we do is.

370
00:19:06,381 --> 00:19:08,821
Once that winning option is chosen.

371
00:19:09,894 --> 00:19:13,416
The player is involved, they go to effectively sprint reviews,

372
00:19:13,456 --> 00:19:14,717
they sign off on concepts,

373
00:19:15,557 --> 00:19:17,098
they're involved as much as we can do.

374
00:19:17,918 --> 00:19:20,600
And as long as their name isn't a My Little Pony reference,

375
00:19:20,980 --> 00:19:21,961
or just the number of digits,

376
00:19:22,221 --> 00:19:23,461
we try to put them in game too,

377
00:19:23,761 --> 00:19:24,962
give that kind of credit to them.

378
00:19:26,003 --> 00:19:26,883
So we tried this for a year,

379
00:19:27,363 --> 00:19:30,165
and one third of our game content was done in this way,

380
00:19:30,285 --> 00:19:31,946
was generated as player designs.

381
00:19:33,283 --> 00:19:34,744
Just quickly go over some good practice.

382
00:19:35,485 --> 00:19:37,226
The first two we learned through our own mistakes.

383
00:19:38,487 --> 00:19:39,508
Bring RuneLabs in-game.

384
00:19:39,548 --> 00:19:41,910
So bring your system for generating

385
00:19:42,330 --> 00:19:44,872
and upvoting player ideas in-game.

386
00:19:45,793 --> 00:19:48,275
We didn't do this, and what we found was

387
00:19:48,395 --> 00:19:50,677
player ideas are not generated from having

388
00:19:50,957 --> 00:19:53,699
a book by the side of their bed for dream ideas

389
00:19:54,179 --> 00:19:54,680
or anything like this.

390
00:19:54,700 --> 00:19:57,702
They're not molyneuing just randomly.

391
00:19:57,922 --> 00:20:00,164
Their ideas are generated by playing the game.

392
00:20:00,745 --> 00:20:01,906
They come across something in the game.

393
00:20:02,767 --> 00:20:03,867
And they have an idea for it.

394
00:20:04,308 --> 00:20:06,249
That was largely where all of the player ideas came from.

395
00:20:06,269 --> 00:20:08,010
Talk a little bit more about that in a moment.

396
00:20:09,411 --> 00:20:11,733
So if the ReLab system is in game, it can do that.

397
00:20:12,645 --> 00:20:15,526
Ensure a fair and dynamic trending algorithms.

398
00:20:15,646 --> 00:20:18,586
Obviously, iTunes and other systems suffer from this.

399
00:20:18,826 --> 00:20:21,727
We found that good ideas were not necessarily rising to the top,

400
00:20:21,947 --> 00:20:24,208
because our trending algorithms were not strong.

401
00:20:25,128 --> 00:20:27,229
And often, setting criteria for the players,

402
00:20:27,369 --> 00:20:29,790
limiting the space for the idea, generated more.

403
00:20:30,530 --> 00:20:32,370
We found that just saying, give us any old idea,

404
00:20:32,790 --> 00:20:36,091
would give us 50% less in terms of ideas, fewer ideas,

405
00:20:36,611 --> 00:20:38,912
than if we said, create a quest with flying bears.

406
00:20:41,984 --> 00:20:45,887
So the flaws, oh actually, I might just skip back quickly here.

407
00:20:45,907 --> 00:20:48,348
So we did kind of contingency work to try to figure out

408
00:20:48,388 --> 00:20:50,209
what we thought the problems would be for RuneLabs.

409
00:20:50,449 --> 00:20:52,110
We sat down and discussed it, we tried to plan for them,

410
00:20:52,391 --> 00:20:55,853
and our worries were that the ideas would be unworkable.

411
00:20:56,733 --> 00:20:59,794
They would be massive. They'd be massively overpowered. It would create power creep.

412
00:21:00,395 --> 00:21:02,236
The ideas that were simply unworkable.

413
00:21:02,316 --> 00:21:04,697
We thought those were the ideas that would come from the user base.

414
00:21:05,077 --> 00:21:07,839
We thought that we'd be culling so many of them

415
00:21:08,319 --> 00:21:10,920
that players would kind of be disengaged from the whole process

416
00:21:11,181 --> 00:21:14,042
because none of the kind of the top ideas were getting into the game.

417
00:21:14,883 --> 00:21:16,804
That wasn't the case. In fact, players were low-balling.

418
00:21:17,124 --> 00:21:20,706
They really wanted their content in the game, so they went smaller than the criteria that we set them.

419
00:21:21,492 --> 00:21:25,195
They really wanted that content in-game. We were completely blown away by that.

420
00:21:25,875 --> 00:21:29,418
The problems with RuneLabs were that there was hugely limited engagement.

421
00:21:30,700 --> 00:21:35,183
In terms of submitting, only 1 in 100 of our player base ever submitted an idea.

422
00:21:36,344 --> 00:21:38,606
So we started trying to drill down into why that was the case.

423
00:21:40,365 --> 00:21:45,710
The first one the players told us was there were a number of obstacles to putting an idea into the game was too large.

424
00:21:46,170 --> 00:21:53,436
They had to create an idea, or to come up with an idea, write it, post it, wait for feedback, and wait to see the numbers, and they got polled.

425
00:21:53,456 --> 00:21:55,638
The number of obstacles were too large.

426
00:21:55,959 --> 00:21:59,282
They also were kind of riding naked through the court of public opinion.

427
00:21:59,902 --> 00:22:00,603
They were worried about that.

428
00:22:00,973 --> 00:22:03,994
They're really worried about being kind of humiliated by their friends.

429
00:22:04,514 --> 00:22:07,295
But once we drilled down, we could find exactly why

430
00:22:07,735 --> 00:22:10,016
players were not interested in submitting their own ideas.

431
00:22:10,916 --> 00:22:15,098
The reason was, they were perfectly happy with the contract between developer and consumer.

432
00:22:15,718 --> 00:22:18,479
They liked being given game content and then playing it.

433
00:22:19,099 --> 00:22:22,160
They weren't interested in expanding that contract anymore, thank you very much.

434
00:22:22,380 --> 00:22:24,301
They were perfectly happy with being delivered content.

435
00:22:25,542 --> 00:22:26,822
And that was kind of the core of the player base.

436
00:22:27,692 --> 00:22:32,437
We also found that upvoting, some options were winning

437
00:22:33,037 --> 00:22:35,119
by only having 100 upvotes.

438
00:22:35,599 --> 00:22:38,362
That meant 1 1 100th of a percent of our player base

439
00:22:38,682 --> 00:22:42,566
were determining content for 1 3rd of our updates.

440
00:22:43,347 --> 00:22:44,848
That was vastly disproportional.

